## Summary of Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Sync algorithm | OT (server-centric) | Simpler with central server |
| Transport | WebSocket | Bidirectional, low latency |
| Conflict resolution | Server as source of truth | Consistent ordering |
| Storage | MongoDB + Cassandra | Flexible docs + time-series ops |
| Scaling | Sticky sessions + Redis | Minimize cross-server coordination |
| Offline | IndexedDB + operation queue | Seamless reconnection |
| Presence | Cursor broadcast + throttling | Real-time awareness |

Answer: A real-time collaborative document editor requires WebSocket connections for low-latency communication, Operational Transformation (OT) or CRDTs for conflict resolution, a server acting as source of truth for operation ordering, optimistic local updates for responsiveness, operation logging for history/replay, periodic snapshots for performance, sticky session load balancing by document ID, Redis Pub/Sub for cross-server coordination, and IndexedDB for offline support with operation queuing on reconnect. | Confidence: 82%
